What the Program Does

The packet sniffer:

Captures live packets from the network
Identifies packet protocols
Extracts IP addresses and port numbers
Displays payload data when available
Counts packets continuously
Shows timestamps for each packet
Stops safely when interrupted
Step 2: Break the Problem into Small Sub-Tasks
Sub-Task 1: Import Required Libraries

The program imports:

scapy → for capturing and analyzing packets
datetime → for timestamps
Sub-Task 2: Display Ethical Warning

Before packet sniffing starts, the program displays an ethical notice reminding users to use the tool responsibly.

Sub-Task 3: Create Packet Counter

A variable stores the number of packets captured during execution.

Every new packet increases the counter by 1.

Sub-Task 4: Process Captured Packets

A function processes every captured packet.

This function:

Identifies the protocol
Extracts source and destination information
Displays payload data if available
Sub-Task 5: Check IP Layer

The program first checks whether the packet contains an IP layer.

This avoids errors and ensures valid packet processing.

Sub-Task 6: Detect Protocol Type

The program checks if the packet uses:

TCP

Used for:

Websites
Emails
File transfers
UDP

Used for:

Streaming
Gaming
Voice calls
ICMP

Used for:

Ping commands
Network diagnostics
Sub-Task 7: Extract Packet Information

The sniffer extracts:

Source IP address
Destination IP address
Source port
Destination port

This helps identify:

Who sent the packet
Where it is going
Sub-Task 8: Extract Payload Data

If the packet contains data, the program displays it.

Otherwise, it shows:

“No payload data”
Sub-Task 9: Start Packet Sniffing

The program continuously listens for packets in real time.

Every captured packet is automatically sent to the processing function.

Sub-Task 10: Graceful Exit

When the user presses Ctrl + C:

Packet sniffing stops safely
Total captured packets are displayed
Stop time is shown
